{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524063"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:01:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:01:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13972"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13972"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.22,0.24,0.37,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6606"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54021"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6606"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13972"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39493"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"904"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13365"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16142"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40218"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54021"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of worsening constipation and abdominal discomfort. She reports no passage of flatus for the past 24 hours. She has a history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include amlodipine and paracetamol. She has no significant family history and has never undergone colonoscopy screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable with a pulse rate of 92/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended and tympanic to percussion, with generalised tenderness but no guarding or rebound. Bowel sounds are high-pitched and tinkling. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis based on the CT findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pseudo-obstruction","Sigmoid volvulus","Caecal volvulus","Obstructing sigmoid cancer","Rectal tumour"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT image shows features consistent with an \u003Cstrong\u003Eobstructing sigmoid cancer\u003C/strong\u003E. This is evidenced by focal wall thickening and luminal narrowing in the sigmoid colon, with proximal colonic dilatation. The clinical presentation of progressive constipation culminating in complete obstruction in an elderly patient is also typical of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a more acute onset and would show a \u0027coffee bean\u0027 or \u0027bird\u0027s beak\u0027 sign on CT, with a twisted mesentery. These features are not present in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaecal volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E would present with dilatation and possible twisting of the caecum and ascending colon, which is not seen here. The obstruction in this case is clearly in the sigmoid region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erectal tumour\u003C/strong\u003E would be located more distally and would typically not cause such significant proximal colonic dilatation without also involving the sigmoid colon. This CT slice is also too superior to show a rectal tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudo-obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as Ogilvie\u0027s syndrome, presents with colonic dilatation without a mechanical obstruction. In this case, there is a clear obstructing lesion visible in the sigmoid colon, ruling out pseudo-obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EObstructing sigmoid cancer is a common cause of large bowel obstruction in elderly patients, especially those who have not undergone regular colorectal cancer screening. The gradual onset of symptoms over two weeks, progressing to complete obstruction, is characteristic. CT is the imaging modality of choice for diagnosing large bowel obstruction and its cause, providing detailed information about the site and nature of the obstruction, as well as potential complications such as perforation or metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Obstructing sigmoid cancer is a common cause of large bowel obstruction in elderly patients.","CT scan is the imaging modality of choice for diagnosing large bowel obstruction and its cause.","Key CT findings of obstructing sigmoid cancer include focal wall thickening, luminal narrowing, and proximal colonic dilatation."],"references":["Pavlidis ET, Galanis IN, Pavlidis TE. Management of obstructed colorectal carcinoma in an emergency setting: An update. World J Gastrointest Oncol. 2024 Mar 15;16(3):598-613. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10989363/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39493"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13972"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20865"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21057"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20865"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/VLf5kmmM7